aulconer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Faulkner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Faulkner","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>fauconer</i>, <i>fauk(e)ner</i>, <i>falconer</i> ‘falconer’ (Old French <i>fau(l)connier</i>), an occupational name for someone who kept and trained falcons (a common feudal service). Falconry was a tremendously popular sport among the aristocracy in medieval Europe, and most great houses had their falconers. The surname could also have arisen as a metonymic occupational name for someone who operated the siege gun known as a <i>falcon</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Faulconer Knight had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Cicely Faulconer."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1225–Female":"1225–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1225":"1225","about 1225":"umbes 1225","Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"–":"Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1225–Female":"1225–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1225":"1225","about 1225":"noin 1225","Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England":"Thurcaston, Leicestershire, England"},"fr":{"–":"Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1225–Fema